<a href="javascript:card_browser(313)">Cave Troll&#39;s Hammer</a><br />
<br />
Conditions:<br />
Goblin <a href="javascript:card_browser(303)">Armor</a>y x4<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(91)">They Are Coming</a> x3<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(78)">Goblin Swarms</a><br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(90)">Relics of Moria</a><br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(960)">Dark Places</a><br />
=42 cards<br />
<br />
Total of 84 cards<br />
<br />
Adventure Deck<br />
1 East Wall of Rohan<br />
2 Uruk Camp<br />
3 Golden Hall<br />
4 White Rocks<br />
5 Hornburg Parâpet<br />
6 Caves of Aglarond<br />
7 Cavern Entrance<br />
8 Wizard&#39;s Vale<br />
9 Orthanc Library    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> As i said, this is the deck that i used to win the Kentucky ToC.  It uses powerful companions with Trust Me to lose not so many skirmishes.  This deck can run pretty well, especially late, when it&#39;s all set up.  Sometimes it&#39;ll win with the O Elbereth/Filibert combo, sometimes it&#39;s minions will get the job done, and some games are a little too close for comfort.  Remember: you have 84 cards, and multiple copies of most things, so you can throw liberally to They Are Coming.  In fact, once thishimmers the board, you should be reconciling 6-8 cards per Shadow turn, not counting any cards you drew with scimitars.  On the FP side, Lindenroot functions as a mini-TAC, and can help you cycle cards.  I almost always throw the first Aragorn, but that is just preference, i suppose.  <br />
<br /><br />
<br />
<br /><br />
As for specific choices:<br />
<br /><br />
<br />
<br /><br />
Ithilien Trap:  This was a last minute switch on the advice of a fellow player, clayton.  He says he likes it to tclobernquea.  It probably works, but this card usually got thrown.  I managed to get one counter on it all day, and then played Grown Suddenly Tall.  It should have been the third Defend it and Hope (which is what i cut for it).<br />
<br /><br />
<br />
<br /><br />
Deep In Thought:  Though there is the chance you will be unable to play this card (lacking 4 twilight), it can still be thrown to Lindenroot.  Roll of Thunder can add 3 in the Maneuver phase.  Keep in mind, against Moria, Dunland, and Greed, there is usually excess twilight, especially with this FP and the massive amounts it gives.  Think of it as half a 10 power companion, at worst, and effective Shadow condition removal at best.<br />
<br /><br />
<br />
<br /><br />
Roll of Thunder:  It adds 3, triggering Gandalf and his staff and helping Deep in Thought, and it kills Palantir, a card this deck absolutely hates.<br />
<br /><br />
4 Cave Troll:  Man, there was at least one game where 4 cave trolls were the only significant minions i played all game, and still won.  This guy is just huge.  And the twilight isn&#39;t really an issue.  If you get an early troll, don&#39;t be afraid to throw it away.  Actually, don&#39;t be too afraid to throw away ANY card, except for really important one-ofs.<br />
<br /><br />
<br />
<br /><br />
Desert Lord:  This guy stops many archery abilities, like Greenleaf, Aragorn&#39;s Bow, and Gondor Bowmen.  Also, he sets up the cave troll pretty well i think.  "What, you have Faramir and Boromir?  I&#39;ll do one to each of them?  Now who will fight the cave troll?"  Mwwwahhh ha ha.<br />
<br /><br />
<br />
<br /><br />
Cards you don&#39;t see:<br />
<br /><br />
Grima, any variety:  Other players play it, so i don&#39;t have to, right?  I played against decks that broke the "grima rules," and i owned them like the rest, so i dunno.<br />
<br /><br />
<br />
<br /><br />
This section will be called "...But what do you do about...?"<br />
<br /><br />
<br />
<br /><br />
Enquea:  I have defend it and hope, so enquea probably only gets two kicks on somebody, which is usually boromir or Gandalf, and it takes more than that to kill those guys.<br />
<br /><br />
<br />
<br /><br />
Tower Assassinin&#39;, Ally Hatin&#39; Uruks:  Watch out for the guys who become 11 and fierce.  Honestly, this deck owns uruks of most varieties.<br />
<br /><br />
<br />
<br /><br />
Fellowship Archery:  People seem to think moria scoops to archery.  This just isn&#39;t true.  I can soak up quite a bit, and armory and Desert Lord stop a lot of that silliness.  <br />
<br /><br />
<br />
<br /><br />
<br />
<br /><br />
MVPs:<br />
<br /><br />
<br />
<br /><br />
It&#39;s hard to name FP MVPs, cuz the deck relies on most of its cards.  I&#39;ll name just a few for each side.<br />
<br /><br />
<br />
<br /><br />
O Elbereth and Filibert:  Anybody really surprised that these cards get named?  Simply put, they win games.  I won two games in the ToC cuz my opponent had a Nazgul in play at site 9.  <br />
<br /><br />
<br />
<br /><br />
Lindenroot: This guy, with 10 power, is just massive.  He has the ability to throw away 2 cards to allow him to skirmish.  You can do it as many times a turn as you have cards to throw.  Add in his ability to squash Isengard minions and you have one of the best companions ever printed.<br />
<br /><br />
<br />
<br /><br />
Sam, Son of Hamfast:  He removes any burdens i happen to get, including the 2-3 i generally bid.  And he can take the ring in a pinch.<br />
<br /><br />
<br />
<br /><br />
Cave Troll:  I just can&#39;t say enough about this guy.  If you play him, and you play TAC, play 4.<br />
<br /><br />
<br />
<br /><br />
Desert Lord:  I think this guy was a factor in every game i played.  He makes the archery math really fuzzy for choke decks, and can deter companions from fighting the cave troll.<br />
<br /><br />
<br />
<br /><br />
They Are Coming:  This is the most important card in the deck.  Without TAC, you can&#39;t cycle as quickly.  The deck would have to be 10-14 cards smaller without it.<br />
<br /><br />
<br />
<br /><br />
Obviously, i think all my cards are MVPs (except the Trap, blah!).  <br />
<br /><br />
<br />
<br /><br />
<br />
<br /><br />
<br />
<br /><br />
UPDATE 5/20/03<br />
I&#39;m trying to switch this deck to Standard.  Any ideas are appreciated.  I think moria can still survive, as you just add more enquea.  Maybe cut it down to 82 cards.  ANybody going to continentals and worlds wanna share decktech? </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font class="bfont"> <a href="/lotr/decks/decks.php">Back to Decks Directory</a> | <A HREF="/lotr/decks/decks.php?reviews=28598"> Read Reviews </A> | <a href="deckprint.php?deck=28598" TARGET="BLANK_"> Printer Friendly</a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><a name="review"></a><font class="h2font">In order to review decks you must be a registered member. <A href="/lotr/main/join.php">Sign up for free!</A></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
